What is an Interface?
An interface defines behavior, not data.

type Speaker interface {
    Speak() string
}
ğŸ“Œ It only contains method signatures.

---- Implicit Implementation (VERY IMPORTANT)

type Person struct{}
func (p Person) Speak() string {
    return "Hello"
}

âœ” Person implements Speaker
âœ” No implements keyword
âœ” Automatically done

---- Using Interface
func saySomething(s Speaker) {
    fmt.Println(s.Speak())
}

4ï¸âƒ£ Interface as Function Parameter (COMMON)
func print(s fmt.Stringer) {
    fmt.Println(s.String())
}
ğŸ“Œ Enables loose coupling.

5ï¸âƒ£ Interface as Return Type
func getSpeaker() Speaker {
    return Person{}
}
âœ” Return behavior, not concrete type.

6ï¸âƒ£ Empty Interface (interface{}) (IMPORTANT)
var x interface{}
x = 10
x = "Go"

âœ” Can hold any type
ğŸ“Œ Used before Go 1.18 (generics)

7ï¸âƒ£ Type Assertion
v := x.(int)
âŒ Panic if wrong type.

âœ” Safe version:
v, ok := x.(int)

8ï¸âƒ£ Type Switch (INTERVIEW FAVORITE)
switch v := x.(type) {
case int:
    fmt.Println("int", v)
case string:
    fmt.Println("string", v)
default:
    fmt.Println("unknown")
}


9ï¸âƒ£ Interface with Pointer Receiver (TRICKY)
  type Writer interface {
      Write()
  }
  
  type File struct{}
  func (f *File) Write() {}

âœ” Only *File implements Writer
âŒ File does NOT
ğŸ“Œ Interview trap

ğŸ”Ÿ Interface Zero Value
var s Speaker

Zero value = nil
Calling method â†’ panic

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ Nil Interface vs Nil Concrete Value (VERY IMPORTANT)
var p *Person = nil
var s Speaker = p

âŒ s != nil
ğŸ“Œ Interface = (type, value)
Type exists â†’ interface not nil.

1ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ Interface Embedding

type Reader interface {
    Read()
}

type Writer interface {
    Write()
}

type ReadWriter interface {
    Reader
    Writer
}
âœ” Composition of behaviors.


1ï¸âƒ£3ï¸âƒ£ Common Standard Interfaces
Interface                	Purpose
error                    	error handling
fmt.Stringer	            string formatting
io.Reader	                read data
io.Writer                	write data

1ï¸âƒ£4ï¸âƒ£ Custom Error Interface Example
type MyError struct {
    Msg string
}

func (e MyError) Error() string {
    return e.Msg
}

1ï¸âƒ£5ï¸âƒ£ Interface Performance (INTERVIEW)
Interface call = slight overhead
Use interfaces at boundaries
Accept interfaces, return structs
ğŸ“Œ Go proverb

1ï¸âƒ£6ï¸âƒ£ When to Use Interface?
âœ” Multiple implementations
âœ” Dependency injection
âœ” Testing (mocking)
âœ” Decoupling

1ï¸âƒ£7ï¸âƒ£ When NOT to Use Interface?
âŒ Only one implementation
âŒ Premature abstraction

1ï¸âƒ£8ï¸âƒ£ Common Interview Traps
âŒ Expecting explicit implementation
âŒ Pointer vs value receiver confusion
âŒ Nil interface confusion
âŒ Overusing empty interface

Interface
An interface defines a set of method signatures that a type must implement.

Implicit Implementation
Go uses implicit interface implementation without an implements keyword.

Empty Interface
An empty interface can hold values of any type.






